{"message":"October 20, 2015 - All right of ways are easements, but not all easements are right of ways. - Restrictive covenant can be removed by mutual agreement, apply for in court and judge agrees, if its an ethnic restricted covenants. - A licence does not have right to a land. A lease has the right in the land. Chapter 3 Registry system. The Old System that existed a long time ago. The way it work, you go down to the office and go into abstract books and look at chain of title which is 40 years back on a property, must make sure that was no problems with the chain 
 of title for the property and all surrounding properties. Once we confirm that there is no problems we write a letter to say it is cleared. If you are in the registry act and someone has a fence on your property for 10 years or if they have an easement for 20 years they acquire interest to your land. Land Title System. New system, everything is registered electronically and all issues with titles have been resolved and registered. Land with issues on title will not be transferred to the Land title system (There are currently about 3500 properties in Ontario that is still on the Registry system (Old System). Mirror principle. The register of title is a mirror that accurately and completely reflects, beyond all argument, the current facts that are material to a person’s title (What you see is what you get) (There is no prescription). The curtain Principle. The register is the sole source of information for proposed buyers, who need not and indeed must not, concern themselves
  with thrust and equities that lie behind this curtain of information. (You don’t need to lift up the curtain to see who owns it). The insurance principle. The mirror (Register) is deemed to give the absolute correct reflection of title, but if through human error a flaw appears, anyone who suffers los must be put in the same position, so far as money can do, that he would have been in had the reflection been a true one. (If there is a problem on title the government will pay to resolve this). Right of survivorship. The right of survivorship is an important aspect of joint tenancy in that the interest of the deceased tenant (Owner) in automatically transferred to the surviving tenant (Owner). This means that, if one joint tenant dies, his/her interest does not pass to his/her estate. (Such as a personal representative or to heirs) but passes directly to the surviving joint tenant or tenants."}

{"message":"Chapter 3. Mini Review 1. A quit claim deed can be an expedient method to resolve a mortgagor’s financial difficulties by vesting all rights associated with the property to the mortgagee. True. A quit claim deed can be effective in this situation, but the mortgagee should be cautious because any existing problems are transferred along with the rights. 2. Under the land titles, the curtain principle states that the register of title accurately and completely reflects current facts about a property title. False. The description provided describes the mirror principle, not the curtain principle. 3. The charge/Mortgage of land can only be used to register mortgages under land titles and not registry. False. The Charge/Mortgage of land is used in both land titles and registry. 4. While the basis for modern land description was originally ba
 sed on lots and concessions, this approach is no longer used as electronic registration requires that properties be identified by lot and plan number. False. Legal descriptions based on lot and concession are widely used in rural areas. 5. Title insurance policies are primarily designed for tow target markets. Lenders and owners. True. Policies and scope of coverage’s for these two audiences will vary by lender. 6. A survey is not required when a buyer obtains title insurance. False. Title insurance may eliminate the need for a survey, but that will depend on the property and the title insurer. 7. The seller’s solicitor must undertake a title search of the property and provide a list of outstanding encumbrances to the buyer. False The buyer’s solicitor, not the sellers solicitor, undertakes a title seach of the property being purchased. 8. Non title search items could include compliance with zoning and the existence of any work orders. True. The two examples highlighte
 d are non title search items. The range of such items will vary by property and individual circumstances. 9. The seller’s lawyer is responsible for preparing a draft transfer/deed of land in preparation for closing a residential transaction. True. The seller’s lawyer also prepares the statement of adjustment. 10. The electronic conversion of land registry records is driven by two systems. Teraview and teranet. False. The two systems are polaris and teraview. Teranet is the company that owns and operates the teraview software."}
